ed form of   O'Callaghan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"O'Callaghan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Liam, Dermot, Donal, Kiernan, Niall, Conor, Donovan, John Patrick, Kieran, Siobhan, Tiernan.","Irish (Cork): from Gaelic <b>Ó Ceallacháin</b>, see   Callahan  ."]}]},{"name":"Mawd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["From the vocabulary word denoting the plant (Old English <i>fearn</i>). Modern use of this word as a given name dates from the 19th century, when it is also recorded occasionally as a boy's name in the United States. In some instances the given name may be a transferred use of the surname derived in the medieval period from the vocabulary word."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mawd ferch Owain was born about 1349, in Glyntawe, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Dafydd  ap Dafydd."},"et":{"ABT    1349–":"umbes 1349–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1349–Female":"1349–Surnud","1349":"1349","1287":"1287","1330":"1330","ABT    1349":"umbes 1349","of Glyntawe,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Glyntawe, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","{Blddn ap Mnrch}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Itaalia"},"fi":{"ABT    1349–":"noin 1349–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1287–Male":"1287–Kuollut","1349–Female":"1349–Kuollut","1349":"1349","1287":"1287","1330":"1330","ABT    1349":"noin 1349","of Glyntawe,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Glyntawe, Breconshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","{Blddn ap Mnrch}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italia"},"fr":{"ABT    1349–":"environ 1349–Décédée","1330–Male":"1330–Décédé","1287–Male":"1287–Décédé","1349–Female":"1349–Décédée","1349":"1349","1287":"1287","1330":"1330","ABT    1349":"environ 1349","of Glyntawe,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Glyntawe, Breconshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","{Blddn ap Mnrch}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italie","lifeSummary":"Mawd ferch Owain est née environ 1349, à Glyntawe, Breconshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Dafydd  ap Dafydd."},"de":{"ABT    1349–":"um 1349–Verstorben","1330–Male":"1330–Verstorben","1287–Male":"1287–Verstorben","1349–Female":"1349–Verstorben","1349":"1349","1287":"1287","1330":"1330","ABT    1349":"um 1349","of Glyntawe,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Glyntawe, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","{Blddn ap Mnrch}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italien","lifeSummary":"Mawd ferch Owain wurde um 1349 in Glyntawe, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom geboren. Sie hatte mit Dafydd  ap Dafydd mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"ABT    1349–":"about 1349